<h2><a name="log" id="log">log</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cmath&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">double</span> log<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> num <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span></pre>
<p>

The function log() returns the natural (base e) logarithm of num. There&#039;s a
domain error if num is negative, a range error if num is zero.
In order to calculate the logarithm of x to an arbitrary base b, you can use:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="kw4">double</span> answer <span class="sy0">=</span> log<span class="br0">&#40;</span>x<span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="sy0">/</span> log<span class="br0">&#40;</span>b<span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span></pre>
<p>
C++ also provides the following overloaded forms:

</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cmath&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">float</span> log<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">float</span> num <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span> <span class="co1">// same as logf() in C99</span>
    <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> log<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> num <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span> <span class="co1">// same as logl() in C99</span></pre>
<p>
Related Topics: <a href="exp" class="wikilink1" title="c:math:exp">exp</a>, <a href="log10" class="wikilink1" title="c:math:log10">log10</a>, <a href="pow" class="wikilink1" title="c:math:pow">pow</a>, <a href="sqrt" class="wikilink1" title="c:math:sqrt">sqrt</a>
</p>

